---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const files = [
  ["schema.sixpack", "logical schema truth"],
  ["tables/**/*.6", "canonical append-only row operations"],
  ["engine/*.6b", "current generated binary row pointers and lookup indexes"],
  ["engine/state.6pack", "target private generated engine-state pack"],
  ["engine/*.6x", "reserved generated full-text index"],
  ["sixpack.toml", "compact recoverable engine metadata"],
];
---

<BaseLayout title="sixpack file format" description="Current sixpack file layout and format rules.">
  <article class="doc-page">
    <section class="doc-hero">
      <div class="doc-wrap">
        <p class="doc-kicker">/ file format</p>
        <h1 class="doc-title">One durable source, rebuildable acceleration.</h1>
        <p class="doc-lead">
          A sixpack directory separates human-readable truth from generated
          runtime state. <code>schema.sixpack</code> and <code>.6</code> table
          segments are canonical. Binary files exist to make normal access fast.
          The target direction keeps those binary internals in one private
          rebuildable engine-state pack.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap">
        <p class="doc-kicker">/ layout</p>
        <h2 class="doc-section-title">Database directory today.</h2>
        <pre class="doc-code"><code>my-app.sixpack/
  schema.sixpack
  sixpack.toml
  tables/
    users/
      zzz.6
      zzy.6
    messages/
      zzz.6
  engine/
    users.6b
    messages.6b
    messages.6x</code></pre>
        <div class="doc-table">
          {files.map(([name, body]) => (
            <div>
              <strong>{name}</strong>
              <span>{body}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap doc-split">
        <div>
          <p class="doc-kicker">/ target layout</p>
          <h2 class="doc-section-title">One generated state pack.</h2>
          <p class="doc-copy">
            The folder remains the database. Table directories remain readable.
            Generated row pointers, lookup maps, counts, source hashes, and
            future search state move behind one private rebuildable file.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre class="doc-code"><code>my-app.sixpack/
  schema.sixpack
  sixpack.toml
  tables/
    users/
      zzz.6
      zzy.6
    messages/
      zzz.6
  engine/
    state.6pack</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap doc-split">
        <div>
          <p class="doc-kicker">/ .6</p>
          <h2 class="doc-section-title">Readable row segments.</h2>
          <p class="doc-copy">
            <code>.6</code> files are append-only table segments. <code>R</code>
            records write a full replacement row. <code>D</code> records write
            a delete tombstone by id. The table can be recovered by replaying
            the segment operations in order.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre class="doc-code"><code>SIX&lt;TAB&gt;1&lt;TAB&gt;table&lt;TAB&gt;messages&lt;TAB&gt;&lt;schema_hash&gt;
@field&lt;TAB&gt;id&lt;TAB&gt;id
@field&lt;TAB&gt;body&lt;TAB&gt;text
@lookup&lt;TAB&gt;id&lt;TAB&gt;unique
@data
R&lt;TAB&gt;1&lt;TAB&gt;m1&lt;TAB&gt;hello
D&lt;TAB&gt;2&lt;TAB&gt;m1</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap doc-split">
        <div class="doc-panel">
          <h2>Escaping</h2>
          <p>
            Text values escape backslash, tab, newline, and carriage return as
            <code>\\</code>, <code>\t</code>, <code>\n</code>, and <code>\r</code>.
            This keeps row lines readable while preserving field boundaries.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="doc-panel">
          <h2>Chunk names</h2>
          <p>
            Table chunks use reverse lowercase base36 names such as
            <code>zzz.6</code>, <code>zzy.6</code>, and <code>zzx.6</code>. The
            naming keeps segment order stable without exposing database
            internals as user API.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap doc-split">
        <div>
          <p class="doc-kicker">/ .6b</p>
          <h2 class="doc-section-title">Generated binary lookup state.</h2>
          <p class="doc-copy">
            <code>.6b</code> files store the binary cache boundary for a table:
            format version, table name, schema hash, source hash, live row
            pointers, and lookup entries. If the cache is missing or stale, it
            can be rebuilt from schema plus <code>.6</code>. The target
            <code>state.6pack</code> file keeps that same generated-state role
            while hiding the per-table cache files.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre class="doc-code"><code>table cache
  version
  schema hash
  source hash
  row id -> row pointer
  lookup field + key -> row ids</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-block">
      <div class="doc-wrap doc-split">
        <div class="doc-panel">
          <h2>sixpack.toml</h2>
          <p>
            Metadata is compact and recoverable. It tracks physical layout and
            engine counters, but it is not the schema and it is not the row
            index. Fresh handles can recover counters from canonical
            <code>.6</code> data.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="doc-panel">
          <h2>.6x</h2>
          <p>
            <code>.6x</code> is reserved for optional generated full-text
            search. Missing <code>.6x</code> files do not affect ids, lookups,
            scans, counts, or normal row reads.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
